# Section 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### **Question 1: Define a self-referential structure. Give a suitable example. [KTU University Exam - May 2024]**

**Model Answer:**

A **self-referential structure** is a structure in which one or more of its members are **pointers pointing to a structure of the same type**. It cannot contain the structure itself as a direct member, because that would result in an infinite-sized structure. However, holding a *pointer* to the same type is valid, since pointers have a fixed size (typically 4 or 8 bytes).

**Example:**
```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;   // pointer to another Node of the same type
};
```

Here, the `next` member is a pointer to a `struct Node`, making the structure self-referential. This forms the building block of **linked lists, trees, and graphs**.

---

### **Question 2: Why can't a structure contain a member that is an instance of itself? How is this limitation overcome? [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]**

**Model Answer:**

A structure **cannot contain a member that is an instance of itself** because that would lead to **infinite recursive memory requirements**. The compiler would try to allocate memory for a `struct Node` that contains another complete `struct Node`, which itself contains another `struct Node`, and so on — resulting in an **infinite size** and a compilation error.

**How the limitation is overcome:**

This is overcome by using a **pointer member** that points to the same structure type. A pointer has a **fixed size** (independent of the structure it points to), so the compiler can allocate a definite amount of memory.

```c
struct Node {
    int data;             // 4 bytes
    struct Node *next;    // 8 bytes (on 64-bit) — FIXED SIZE
};
```

The total size of this structure is therefore finite (e.g., 16 bytes including padding), and nodes can be linked dynamically using `malloc()`.

---

## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Scheme Rule:** Part B questions of a module offer an **internal choice**. You must answer **either** Question A **or** Question B. Each carries 14 marks, typically split as **(a) 7 marks + (b) 7 marks**.

---

### **Question A (14 Marks): [KTU University Exam - Dec 2024]**

**Define a self-referential structure to represent a node of a singly linked list storing integer data.**

**(a)** Write a complete C program to:
- Create three nodes dynamically with values 100, 200, and 300.
- Link them together to form a linked list.
- Display the contents of the list.

**(b)** Explain the memory layout of the above linked list with a suitable diagram. What is the total memory consumed by the three nodes on a 64-bit system?

#### **Model Solution for (a) — 7 Marks**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

typedef struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
} Node;

int main() {
    Node *head = NULL, *second = NULL, *third = NULL;

    // Allocate three nodes
    head     = (Node *)malloc(sizeof(Node));
    second   = (Node *)malloc(sizeof(Node));
    third    = (Node *)malloc(sizeof(Node));

    // Assign data
    head->data     = 100;
    second->data   = 200;
    third->data    = 300;

    // Link the nodes
    head->next     = second;
    second->next   = third;
    third->next    = NULL;

    // Traverse and display
    printf("Linked List contents: ");
    Node *ptr = head;
    while (ptr != NULL) {
        printf("%d -> ", ptr->data);
        ptr = ptr->next;
    }
    printf("NULL\n");

    // Free memory
    free(head);
    free(second);
    free(third);

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
Linked List contents: 100 -> 200 -> 300 -> NULL
```

**Mark Distribution (typical KTU pattern):**
- Structure definition: **2 marks**
- Dynamic allocation of nodes: **2 marks**
- Linking logic: **1.5 marks**
- Traversal & display: **1 mark**
- Proper `free()` and cleanup: **0.5 marks**

#### **Model Solution for (b) — 7 Marks**

**Memory Layout Description:**

Each node is a `struct Node` containing an `int data` (4 bytes) and a `struct Node *next` pointer (8 bytes on 64-bit). With **structure padding** to align to 8 bytes, each node occupies **16 bytes** in the heap.

The three nodes are stored at **non-contiguous heap addresses** (e.g., 0x1000, 0x1010, 0x1020), linked solely by the `next` pointers.

**Diagram:**

```
  head
   |
   v
+------+------+      +------+------+      +------+------+
| 100  |  ----|----> | 200  |  ----|----> | 300  | NULL |
+------+------+      +------+------+      +------+------+
  (16 bytes)            (16 bytes)            (16 bytes)
   @0x1000              @0x1010               @0x1020
```

**Total Memory Calculation:**

$$
\text{Total Memory} = 3 \times 16 = 48 \text{ bytes}
$$

**Note:** Additionally, three pointer variables (`head`, `second`, `third`) on the stack consume $3 \times 8 = 24$ bytes, but the *node data* itself uses 48 bytes in the heap.

**Mark Distribution:**
- Memory layout explanation: **3 marks**
- Diagram: **2 marks**
- Calculation: **2 marks**

---

### **Question B (14 Marks): [KTU University Exam - May 2024]**

**(a)** What is a self-referential structure? Differentiate between a structure containing a member of its own type versus a structure containing a pointer to its own type. Illustrate with examples.

**(b)** Write a C program to create a singly linked list of `n` nodes where the user inputs `n` and the data for each node. Display the list in **reverse order** using recursion. Also explain how the self-referential structure enables this recursion.

#### **Model Solution for (a) — 7 Marks**

**Definition:**

A self-referential structure is one where a member is a **pointer to the same structure type**.

**Comparison Table:**

| Aspect | Structure as Direct Member | Pointer to Same Structure |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `struct Node n;` (illegal) | `struct Node *ptr;` (legal) |
| **Compilation** | **Error** (infinite size) | **Success** |
| **Memory size of struct** | Infinite (undefined) | Finite (e.g., 16 bytes) |
| **Use case** | Not allowed in C | Linked lists, trees, graphs |
| **Allocation** | Cannot be done | `malloc(sizeof(struct Node))` |

**Example — ILLEGAL version (will NOT compile):**
```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node next;   // ERROR: invalid — infinite size
};
```

**Example — LEGAL version (the correct approach):**
```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;  // OK: pointer has fixed size
};
```

**Mark Distribution:**
- Definition: **1.5 marks**
- Comparison table: **3 marks**
- Examples (legal + illegal): **2.5 marks**

#### **Model Solution for (b) — 7 Marks**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

typedef struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
} Node;

Node *head = NULL;

// Recursive display in reverse
void displayReverse(Node *ptr) {
    if (ptr == NULL) return;            // base case
    displayReverse(ptr->next);          // recursive call first
    printf("%d -> ", ptr->data);        // print on the way back
}

int main() {
    int n, value;
    Node *newNode = NULL, *temp = NULL;

    printf("Enter number of nodes: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        newNode = (Node *)malloc(sizeof(Node));
        printf("Enter data for node %d: ", i + 1);
        scanf("%d", &value);
        newNode->data = value;
        newNode->next = NULL;

        if (head == NULL) {
            head = newNode;
        } else {
            temp = head;
            while (temp->next != NULL)
                temp = temp->next;
            temp->next = newNode;
        }
    }

    printf("List in original order: ");
    Node *p = head;
    while (p != NULL) {
        printf("%d -> ", p->data);
        p = p->next;
    }
    printf("NULL\n");

    printf("List in reverse order: ");
    displayReverse(head);
    printf("NULL\n");

    return 0;
}
```

**Sample Output:**
```
Enter number of nodes: 3
Enter data for node 1: 10
Enter data for node 2: 20
Enter data for node 3: 30
List in original order: 10 -> 20 -> 30 -> NULL
List in reverse order: 30 -> 20 -> 10 -> NULL
```

**How the Self-Referential Structure Enables This Recursion:**

The function `displayReverse(Node *ptr)` calls itself with `ptr->next`. This works **only** because `next` is a pointer to a node of the same type, allowing the function's parameter to be passed the address of the *next* node. If `next` were the structure itself, infinite compilation would occur and recursion would be conceptually meaningless (and would cause stack overflow at runtime if it somehow compiled).

**Mark Distribution:**
- Correct `struct` and `typedef`: **1 mark**
- Loop for `n` nodes and insertion logic: **2.5 marks**
- Recursive function: **2 marks**
- Correct output and explanation: **1.5 marks**

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls**
> 
> 1. **Forgetting `typedef`** — Many students write `struct Node` everywhere; using `typedef Node` is cleaner and earns brownie marks.
> 2. **Using `=` instead of `==` in conditions** — A classic mistake (`ptr = NULL` is assignment, `ptr == NULL` is comparison).
> 3. **Missing `free()`** — While not always penalized in KTU exams, mentioning `free()` shows good practice and earns partial credit.
> 4. **Confusing `.` and `\rightarrow`** — Use `.` for `struct` variables, `\rightarrow` for pointers. This is one of the **most common** mark-deducting errors.
> 5. **Forgetting `#include <stdlib.h>`** — Without it, `malloc` and `free` declarations are missing, leading to warnings or runtime issues.
> 6. **Illegal direct self-reference** — Writing `struct Node n;` inside `struct Node` is an **instant zero** for that part. Always use a pointer.
> 7. **Not null-terminating the last node** — Always set the last node's `next` to `NULL`, or your traversal will run indefinitely into undefined memory.

---

## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **Rapid-Revision Checklist for Self-Referential Structures**

- **Definition** — A structure that contains a **pointer to a structure of the same type**.
- **Why pointer, not instance?** — Direct inclusion would cause infinite size; pointers have **fixed size** (4 or 8 bytes).
- **Foundation of** — Linked lists, stacks, queues, trees, graphs, hash tables, and any dynamic non-contiguous data structure.
- **Declaration pattern** — `typedef struct Node { int data; struct Node *next; } Node;`
- **Memory allocation** — Always use `malloc(sizeof(struct Node))` to create nodes dynamically.
- **Termination** — Last node's `next` must be `NULL` to mark the end of the chain.
- **Access operators**:
  - `.` (dot) → for `struct` **variables**.
  - `$\rightarrow$` (arrow) → for `struct` **pointers**.
- **`head` pointer** — Required as an entry point to traverse the chain from the beginning.
- **Size formula** — `sizeof(struct Node) = sizeof(int) + sizeof(pointer)` + alignment padding.
- **64-bit size (Pattern 1)** — **16 bytes per node** (with padding).
- **Real-world uses** — OS process lists, Git commits (doubly linked), file systems (trees), DB indexes (B-trees), compiler ASTs.
- **Cleanup** — Always `free()` every dynamically allocated node to prevent memory leaks.
- **No embedded self-reference** — `struct Node n;` inside `struct Node` is a **compilation error**.

> [!TIP]
> **Last-Minute Memory Trick (KTU Viva & Exams):**
> Think **"SPOT"** — **S**tructure, **P**ointer, **O**wn type, **T**raverse via `next`. If you remember SPOT, you remember the entire concept!
