# SECTION 3: STEP-BY-STEP DERIVATIONS, ALGORITHMS & ANALYTICAL MATRIX

## 3.1 Algorithm A — Insertion at the Beginning of a Singly Circular Linked List

### 3.1.1 Conceptual Walkthrough (Why this works)

When we insert a node at the **head** of a non-empty SCLL, the new node becomes the new `head`. The **old tail's `next` pointer must be updated** to point to the new head, because the tail's `next` always points to the head (the circular invariant). If we skip this update, the list becomes a "broken ring" and we lose the last node.

### 3.1.2 Exhaustive C Algorithm

```c
// Step 1: Define the node structure
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};

// Step 2: Function to insert a new node at the beginning
struct Node* insertAtHead(struct Node *head, int value) {
    // Step 2.1: Allocate the new node (dynamic memory)
    struct Node *newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = value;
    newNode->next = NULL;          // Initialize to safe state

    // Step 2.2: Handle Case 1 — Empty list
    if (head == NULL) {
        newNode->next = newNode;   // Self-loop: a 1-node CLL points to itself
        return newNode;
    }

    // Step 2.3: Handle Case 2 — Non-empty list
    // Step 2.3.1: Walk to the tail node (last node, whose next = head)
    struct Node *temp = head;
    while (temp->next != head) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    // Step 2.3.2: Wire the new node to the old head
    newNode->next = head;

    // Step 2.3.3: Update the tail's next to the new head
    temp->next = newNode;

    // Step 2.3.4: Return the new head
    return newNode;
}
```

### 3.1.3 Step-by-Step Logical Trace (5-node example)

Let the initial list be: `10 → 20 → 30 → 40 → 50 → (back to 10)`. We insert `5` at the head.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Initial state:} \quad & \text{head} = 10, \quad \text{tail} = 50, \quad \text{tail} \rightarrow \text{next} = 10 \\
\text{Step 1 (allocate):} \quad & \text{newNode} = 5, \quad \text{newNode} \rightarrow \text{next} = NULL \\
\text{Step 2 (head == NULL?):} \quad & \text{head} = 10 \neq NULL \;\Rightarrow\; \text{skip to Step 3} \\
\text{Step 3 (find tail):} \quad & \text{Walk from 10: } 10 \rightarrow 20 \rightarrow 30 \rightarrow 40 \rightarrow 50 \\
& \text{At 50, } 50 \rightarrow \text{next} = 10 = \text{head, so } \text{temp} = 50 \\
\text{Step 4 (link new to head):} \quad & 5 \rightarrow \text{next} = 10 \\
\text{Step 5 (update tail):} \quad & 50 \rightarrow \text{next} = 5 \\
\text{Final state:} \quad & \text{head} = 5, \quad \text{tail} = 50, \quad 50 \rightarrow \text{next} = 5 \\
& \text{Ring: } 5 \rightarrow 10 \rightarrow 20 \rightarrow 30 \rightarrow 40 \rightarrow 50 \rightarrow 5
\end{aligned}
$$

---

## 3.2 Algorithm B — Insertion at the End of a Singly Circular Linked List

### 3.2.1 Logical Reasoning

Inserting at the tail in an SCLL is symmetric to head insertion. The new node becomes the new tail, and its `next` must point to `head`. The old tail's `next` must be redirected to the new node.

### 3.2.2 Exhaustive C Algorithm

```c
struct Node* insertAtTail(struct Node *head, int value) {
    // Step 1: Allocate the new node
    struct Node *newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = value;
    newNode->next = head;          // New tail points to head (circular invariant)

    // Step 2: Handle empty list case
    if (head == NULL) {
        newNode->next = newNode;   // Self-loop for 1-node list
        return newNode;
    }

    // Step 3: Walk to the old tail
    struct Node *temp = head;
    while (temp->next != head) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    // Step 4: Splice the new node into the ring
    temp->next = newNode;

    // Step 5: head does not change in tail-insertion
    return head;
}
```

### 3.2.3 Analytical Trace

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Initial:} \quad & 10 \rightarrow 20 \rightarrow 30 \rightarrow 40 \rightarrow 50 \rightarrow 10 \\
\text{Allocate:} \quad & \text{newNode} = 60, \quad 60 \rightarrow \text{next} = 10 \; (\text{head}) \\
\text{Find tail:} \quad & \text{Walk: } 10 \rightarrow 20 \rightarrow 30 \rightarrow 40 \rightarrow 50; \; 50 \rightarrow \text{next} = 10, \text{ so } \text{temp} = 50 \\
\text{Splice:} \quad & 50 \rightarrow \text{next} = 60 \\
\text{Final ring:} \quad & 10 \rightarrow 20 \rightarrow 30 \rightarrow 40 \rightarrow 50 \rightarrow 60 \rightarrow 10
\end{aligned}
$$

---

## 3.3 Algorithm C — Deletion of a Node by Value (Singly Circular)

### 3.3.1 Logical Reasoning

There are **three cases** to handle:
1. **Empty list** — nothing to delete.
2. **Single-node list** — free the node, return `NULL`.
3. **Multi-node list** — find the node; if it is the head, update both `head` and tail's `next`; otherwise, splice out the predecessor.

### 3.3.2 Exhaustive C Algorithm

```c
struct Node* deleteNode(struct Node *head, int key) {
    // Case 1: Empty list
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty.\n");
        return NULL;
    }

    // Case 2: Single-node list where head is the key
    if (head->data == key && head->next == head) {
        free(head);
        return NULL;
    }

    // Case 3a: Head has the key (multi-node case)
    struct Node *temp = head;
    if (head->data == key) {
        // Find the tail (whose next currently points to head)
        while (temp->next != head) {
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        // Re-route tail to skip the old head
        temp->next = head->next;
        struct Node *newHead = head->next;
        free(head);
        return newHead;
    }

    // Case 3b: Key is in middle or tail — use two pointers
    struct Node *prev = head;
    struct Node *curr = head->next;
    while (curr != head && curr->data != key) {
        prev = curr;
        curr = curr->next;
    }

    // If found, splice it out
    if (curr != head) {
        prev->next = curr->next;
        free(curr);
    } else {
        printf("Key %d not found in the list.\n", key);
    }
    return head;
}
```

### 3.3.3 Trace: Delete `30` from `10 → 20 → 30 → 40 → 50 → 10`

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Initial:} \quad & \text{head} = 10, \quad 50 \rightarrow \text{next} = 10 \\
\text{Case checks:} \quad & \text{head} \neq NULL, \; \text{head} \rightarrow \text{next} = 20 \neq \text{head} \;\Rightarrow\; \text{Case 3b} \\
\text{Walk with prev/curr:} \quad & \text{prev} = 10, \; \text{curr} = 20 \;(20 \neq 30) \\
& \text{prev} = 20, \; \text{curr} = 30 \;(30 = 30 \;\Rightarrow\; \text{stop}) \\
\text{Splice:} \quad & 20 \rightarrow \text{next} = 40 \\
\text{Free:} \quad & \text{free}(30) \\
\text{Final ring:} \quad & 10 \rightarrow 20 \rightarrow 40 \rightarrow 50 \rightarrow 10
\end{aligned}
$$

