## 3.4 Algorithm D — Traversal (The Universal CLL Iteration Pattern)

```c
void traverse(struct Node *head) {
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node *temp = head;
    // do-while ensures we visit the head at least once
    // and terminates when we circle back to it
    do {
        printf("%d ", temp->data);
        temp = temp->next;
    } while (temp != head);
    printf("\n");
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The `do-while` is the canonical KTU-recommended pattern for CLL traversal.** A `while` loop would print nothing for a 1-node list because the loop-condition would be checked *before* the first print.

---

## 3.5 Algorithm E — Josephus Problem (Classic CLL Application)

The Josephus problem: `n` people stand in a circle; every `k`-th person is eliminated; find the survivor.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Setup:} \quad & \text{Build a CLL of } n \text{ nodes labelled } 1, 2, \ldots, n. \\
\text{Loop invariant:} \quad & \text{Current person is the one to be eliminated next if count} = k. \\
\text{Elimination step:} \quad & \text{prev} \rightarrow \text{next} = \text{curr} \rightarrow \text{next}; \; \text{free(curr);} \; \text{curr} = \text{prev} \rightarrow \text{next}. \\
\text{Repeat until one node remains.}
\end{aligned}
$$

```c
int josephus(int n, int k) {
    // Build the CLL of n nodes
    struct Node *head = NULL, *tail = NULL;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        struct Node *node = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
        node->data = i;
        if (head == NULL) {
            head = tail = node;
            node->next = head;
        } else {
            tail->next = node;
            tail = node;
            tail->next = head;
        }
    }

    // Eliminate every k-th person
    struct Node *prev = tail;
    struct Node *curr = head;
    while (curr->next != curr) {
        for (int i = 1; i < k; i++) {
            prev = curr;
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        prev->next = curr->next;
        free(curr);
        curr = prev->next;
    }
    int survivor = curr->data;
    free(curr);
    return survivor;
}
```

**Closed-form solution (KTU bonus):**

$$
J(n, k) = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if } n = 1 \\ \bigl(J(n-1, k) + k\bigr) \bmod n & \text{if } n > 1 \end{cases}
$$

