> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls (Where Students Lose Marks)**
>
> 1. **Using `while` instead of `do-while` for traversal** — causes the head node to be **skipped in a single-node list** (a 1-node CLL has `head->next == head`, so `while(temp != head)` is false from the start). Use `do-while`. *(−1 to −2 marks)*
> 2. **Forgetting to update the tail's `next` pointer** during head-insertion. This breaks the circular invariant and the last node is **orphaned** (memory leak). *(−2 marks)*
> 3. **Not handling the empty-list case** (`head == NULL`) before any traversal. Causes a `NULL pointer dereference` segmentation fault. *(−1 to −2 marks)*
> 4. **Confusing SCLL and DCLL pointer counts** — in a DCLL, the head's `prev` points to the **tail**, not `NULL`. Students often write `head->prev = NULL`, which is a *fatal* error. *(−2 marks)*
> 5. **Off-by-one in Josephus counting** — the count must start from the **next person**, not the current one. KTU expects `k-1` forward steps before elimination. *(−1 mark)*
> 6. **Memory leak** — forgetting `free()` on deleted nodes. KTU now allocates marks for "proper memory management" in PEEET526. *(−1 mark)*

