## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember (Rapid-Revision Checklist)

> [!NOTE]
> **Final Revision Bullet-Points (Print This Before Exam)**

- [ ] A **Circular Linked List** has **no `NULL`** — the last node's `next` points back to the head.
- [ ] **Two variants:** Singly Circular (1 ptr/node, forward only) and Doubly Circular (2 ptrs/node, bidirectional).
- [ ] **Traversal MUST use `do-while`** — a `while` loop will skip the head in a 1-node list.
- [ ] **Empty list check:** `head == NULL`. **Single-node check:** `head->next == head`.
- [ ] **Insert at head/tail in SCLL** = $O(n)$ because you must walk to the tail. **In DCLL with a `tail` pointer** = $O(1)$.
- [ ] **Delete at head/tail in DCLL** = $O(1)$. **In SCLL** = $O(n)$ due to tail re-routing.
- [ ] **Circular invariant to preserve after every operation:** `tail->next == head`.
- [ ] **Memory per node (SCLL):** $M = n \cdot (S_d + S_p)$. **Memory per node (DCLL):** $M = n \cdot (S_d + 2 S_p)$.
- [ ] **Applications:** Round-robin CPU scheduling, token ring LAN, circular buffers (kernel I/O), Josephus problem, music playlist loop, browser history (DCLL), LRU cache (DCLL).
- [ ] **Josephus closed-form:** $J(n, k) = \bigl(J(n-1, k) + k\bigr) \bmod n$, $J(1, k) = 0$. Survivor index = $J(n, k) + 1$.
- [ ] **DCLL trap:** `head->prev` is the **tail**, not `NULL`. Don't initialize it to `NULL`.
- [ ] **Single-node DCLL:** `head->next == head` AND `head->prev == head` (both pointers self-loop).
- [ ] **Always check for empty list** before traversal/insertion/deletion to avoid segfaults.
- [ ] **Always `free()` deleted nodes** to avoid memory leaks (KTU marks this explicitly).
- [ ] **Insertion dry-run technique:** Draw the ring as a circle, label nodes, and re-draw the arrows after each pointer update — this is exactly how KTU examiners expect you to present your answer.
- [ ] **Deletion dry-run technique:** Identify `prev` and `curr` pointers, advance them in lock-step until `curr` matches the target, then redraw the `prev->next` link to bypass `curr`.

